Suggs, who turns 36 in October, is entering his 16th season with Baltimore, the final remnant of the fearsome defenses this team assembled in the mid-2000s. The linebacker, who started all 16&nbsp;games last season and racked up 11 sacks and 37 solo tackles, parried a question about whether he has thought of retirement &mdash; &ldquo;Nah&rdquo; &mdash; and repeated, six times in 10 minutes, that being able to stay with one franchise this long is &ldquo;flattering.&rdquo;Suggs was once a brash, endearing young player who called himself &ldquo;Sizzle&rdquo; and claimed an education from &ldquo;Ball So Hard University.&rdquo; He had teammates who became friends and mentors &mdash; linebacker Ray Lewis, linebacker Adalius &ldquo;AD&rdquo; Thomas, safety Ed Reed, cornerback Chris McAlister and Ngata. As he looks around now, all of those players are gone from the team and most are out of the NFL. Standing there, alone at the mic, the man who has made a living dispensing brutal hits seemed somehow softer.&ldquo;One of the biggest regrets I always tell these younger guys is that I took [former teammates] for granted,&rdquo; Suggs said, looking down.
